      "source_refs": [
        {
          "path": "literature/2510.23470/arxiv_source/aa57036-25corr_clean.tex",
          "start_line": 197,
          "end_line": 197,
          "context": "The smallest resolvable angle, $\\theta_\\mathrm{min}$, depends highly on the observing wavelength, $\\lambda$, and the arrangement of the array: $\\theta_\\mathrm{min} \\sim \\lambda/B_\\mathrm{max}$, where $B_\\mathrm{max}$ is the length of the largest baseline of the interferometer.\nThe largest observable scale, $\\theta_\\mathrm{max}$, is set by the beamsize of a single component telescope of the interferometer with diameter $D_\\mathrm{tel}$, according to $\\theta_\\mathrm{max}\\sim \\lambda / D_\\mathrm{tel}$,\nFor D-configuration, the observing limits (i.e,~observable angular scales of the target\\footnote{\\url{https://science.nrao.edu/facilities/vla/docs/manuals/oss2019B/performance/resolution}}) are between \\ang{;;12} and \\ang{;;240} for C band, and between \\ang{;;7.2} and \\ang{;;145} for the X band.\nIf the target is outside those limits, the array will not be able to resolve the image or will lose flux on large scales.\nTo decide which of the remaining objects we would include in the observation, we measured the size of the bow shocks from the available IR maps online.\\footnote{\\url{https://aladin.u-strasbg.fr}}"
        }
      ],
      "evidence": "The smallest resolvable angle, $\\theta_\\mathrm{min}$, depends highly on the observing wavelength, $\\lambda$, and the arrangement of the array: $\\theta_\\mathrm{min} \\sim \\lambda/B_\\mathrm{max}$, where $B_\\mathrm{max}$ is the length of the largest baseline of the interferometer.\nThe largest observable scale, $\\theta_\\mathrm{max}$, is set by the beamsize of a single component telescope of the interferometer with diameter $D_\\mathrm{tel}$, according to $\\theta_\\mathrm{max}\\sim \\lambda / D_\\mathrm{tel}$,\nFor D-configuration, the observing limits (i.e,~observable angular scales of the target\\footnote{\\url{https://science.nrao.edu/facilities/vla/docs/manuals/oss2019B/performance/resolution}}) are between \\ang{;;12} and \\ang{;;240} for C band, and between \\ang{;;7.2} and \\ang{;;145} for the X band.\nIf the target is outside those limits, the array will not be able to resolve the image or will lose flux on large scales.\nTo decide which of the remaining objects we would include in the observation, we measured the size of the bow shocks from the available IR maps online.\\footnote{\\url{https://aladin.u-strasbg.fr}}",
      "comments": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "resource-003",
      "kind": "external_url",
